00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:28.200
So, the theme of this year's
conference touches deeply

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:30.840
on the James Truslow
Adams American dream.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:33.620
And I've hinted it-- add
that in my presidential

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.730
or that welcoming note
in the program.

00:05:37.730 --> 00:05:39.030
That became the symbol

00:05:39.030 --> 00:05:41.820
of opportunity, prosperity,
and success.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:44.780
The American dream was
achieved through sacrifice,

00:05:44.780 --> 00:05:46.980
risk-taking and hard work.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.380
All being part of the
entrepreneurial spirit

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:52.120
that became synonyms with America.

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:57.210 position:56%
Adams in his book, "The Epic of
America," which was written in 1931,

00:05:57.210 --> 00:06:00.950
defined the American dream
as that dream of a land

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:05.420
in which life should be better
and richer and fuller for everyone

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:08.620
with opportunity for each
according to their ability

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:11.220
of achievement-- or achievement.

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:14.170
Put one in this sense,
they [inaudible] a parallel

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:18.720
between Adams's American dream
of opportunity and the discovery

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:23.870 position:56%
of recorded sound, images and moving
images, the establishment of radio

00:06:23.870 --> 00:06:28.150
and television, and the consequent
inevitable growth of sound

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:30.340
and audiovisual archives.

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:33.500
With every pioneering
development to record images,

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:37.390
sound and moving images, came
new opportunities to preserve

00:06:37.390 --> 00:06:40.330
and expose our collections
to the world.

00:06:40.330 --> 00:06:44.660
Ensuring that our collections
were meticulously catalogued,

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:48.690
well-preserved and secured in a
physical sense as well as in terms

00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:52.690
of the conflicts and tricky
ownership rights associated

00:06:52.690 --> 00:06:57.310
with the content was certainly
not without risk and hard work.

00:06:57.310 --> 00:07:00.320
I believe that this pattern
of archives being impacted

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:02.980
by new technologies and
maintaining a balance

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:04.830 position:56%
between safeguarding our collections

00:07:04.830 --> 00:07:09.100
and making them accessible has
the ingredients of that trend.

00:07:09.100 --> 00:07:12.720
We have no choice but
to take note of trends

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:15.490
that are shaping the
future of our world.

00:07:15.490 --> 00:07:19.490
Each technological innovation
and the market's response

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:23.660
to the innovations has the makings
of a trend and the potential

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:27.560
to take us forward, or
sadly, in some cases,

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:29.570
put us a step or two back.

00:07:29.570 --> 00:07:34.240
How many of us were not forced
to preserve our audio collections

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.750
on mini disc to save storage space?

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:41.680
And how many of us had to fight the
preservation, of the preservation,

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:44.850
using MP3 for the same reason?

00:07:44.850 --> 00:07:48.950 position:56%
It is a miracle that our collections
sometimes survive this ostensibly

00:07:48.950 --> 00:07:52.610
cost and storage reductions
decisions.

00:07:52.610 --> 00:07:55.590
Today I say, and I speak
on personal experience,

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:59.440
that IASA was the saving
grace in many instances.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:02.520
Trends become discernible
overtime and give us an idea

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:07.000
of what's happening in a particular
field at any given point in time.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.270
Trends provide a view of the
future and hints on how to prepare.

00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:14.870
As the sci-fi author William
Gibson who coined terms

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:20.680
such as cyberspace already in the
1980s, long before anyone used it,

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:26.100
say, "The future is here already,
it's just not evenly distributed."

00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:27.400
Is this not also the case

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:29.560
where audiovisual archives
are now collections

00:08:29.560 --> 00:08:31.690
in the digital landscape?

00:08:31.690 --> 00:08:32.990
We are already connected

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:37.710 position:56%
to our global markets even though we
may not have exposed them fully yet,

00:08:37.710 --> 00:08:39.720
or explored them fully yet.

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:43.240
Do we have a choice about not
thinking more entrepreneurial

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:45.130
about our work and the advantages

00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:48.980
and challenges the digital
landscape offers to us?

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:52.410
In occupying this niche
market, we need to be up-to-date

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:54.140
with the latest technology.

00:08:54.140 --> 00:08:57.410
We need to know what our
constituencies are wanting from us

00:08:57.410 --> 00:09:01.510
and how demands for access to
information affects us in terms

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:03.570
of offerings to our clients.

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:08.460
An associate directory-- director
of the Reference Department

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:13.860
at the Library of Congress, one
John L. Nolan, when writing a 1961

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:16.180
about the inclusion of
audiovisuals as part

00:09:16.180 --> 00:09:18.420
of the library collections noted

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:22.890
that the fast moving technological
changes made projection

00:09:22.890 --> 00:09:26.610
of present trends-- can
I just repeat that --

00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:30.610 position:56%
of fast moving technological changes
made prediction of present trends

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:34.140 position:56%
in this area particularly hazardous.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:36.360
That was in 1961.

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:40.190 position:56%
Acknowledging this-- his postulation
might just have been wishful

00:09:40.190 --> 00:09:41.950
thinking on his part.

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:46.230
Nolan listed the trends then
as, one, greater production

00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:50.500
of audiovisual materials for
educational and recreational use.

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:55.250
According to Nolan, the audiovisual
industry had doubled in the 1950

00:09:55.250 --> 00:10:00.750
to 1960 period and he predicted
a doubling by the end of 1962.

00:10:00.750 --> 00:10:03.250
Two, an urgent need
for trained personnel

00:10:03.250 --> 00:10:07.420
to handle the growing volume and
variety of audiovisual materials,

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:09.690
especially training in
the technical aspects

00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:12.210
of handling audiovisual materials.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:16.820
But adding that, far more important
will be the need for imagination,

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:20.370
initiative, and practical
planning in this field.

00:10:20.370 --> 00:10:24.030
Three, the expansion of
technological research

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:28.470
and development to make possible
greater centralization of service,

00:10:28.470 --> 00:10:31.620
greater simplicity in
use, and lower cost.

00:10:31.620 --> 00:10:37.180
In other words, automization to
permit a greater degree of use

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:41.310
through self service and
thorough mass service--

00:10:41.310 --> 00:10:43.050
sorry, and through mass service.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:47.390
Four, the development of more
systematic bibliographic coverage

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:52.040
and methods of organizing
audiovisual materials for use.

00:10:52.040 --> 00:10:56.210 position:56%
Sixty years later, we see that
Nolan had a good grasp of the future

00:10:56.210 --> 00:10:58.490
and opportunities of the time.

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:02.450
In a recent research
survey done by the OCLC,

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:04.810
the following trends were observed,

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:08.170
growth of especially
audiovisual collections,

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:12.820
growth of online catalogues,
large scale digitization models,

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:17.580
and integration of once
separated special collections.

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:19.820
We see the phenomenal growth

00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:22.970
of audiovisual collections
on a daily basis.

00:11:22.970 --> 00:11:27.350
I do not need to expand on the vast
impact, social media and technology

00:11:27.350 --> 00:11:28.650
such as smartphones

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:32.680
and sophisticated software
are having on our collections.

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:35.260
With this comes the shift
towards for more faults

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:38.320
and fewer physical holdings,
especially in the case

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:43.080
of born-digital content which of
course has its own challenges.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:47.340
The current trend to digitize
archived material increases access

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:51.040
to previously unknown and
unshareable materials,

00:11:51.040 --> 00:11:54.030
those hidden collections,
and opens the potential

00:11:54.030 --> 00:11:56.730
for research and educational use.

00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:58.600
In addition, the usage and value

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:02.890
of previously accessible materials
have both increased as a result

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:05.820
of greater demand for information.

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:10.110 position:56%
Online catalogues have become a
trend, more secure and sophisticated

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:13.640
than ever before in making
audiovisual collections available

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:14.940
to users.

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:18.150
It is impossible not
to think about ITN

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:22.460
and its online catalogue
called ITN Source is an example

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:26.150
of a modern online
catalogue containing more

00:12:26.150 --> 00:12:30.150
than one million hours of
footage and growing at a rate

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:34.040
of over 20 hours of
digital content per day.

00:12:34.040 --> 00:12:37.700
Not only that ITN see the
opportunity to make available

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:42.580
and sell its collection online,
but ITN also partnered with 24

00:12:42.580 --> 00:12:46.030
of the world's most influential
agencies, which includes

00:12:46.030 --> 00:12:50.420
for instance Reuters, and
syndicates its own news footage

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:53.160 position:56%
