00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:30.810
to handle the growing volume and
variety of audiovisual materials.

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:34.320
This potential for partnerships
with commercial entities,

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:39.830
a concept once frowned about
upon but with modern day reality.

00:15:39.830 --> 00:15:45.820
To realize these opportunities
may require remote access 24/7/365

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:49.450
to meet our users' demand for
instant access to our collections.

00:15:49.450 --> 00:15:53.480
This in turn implies building
comprehensive metadata resources

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:57.750
and optimizing the audiovisual
resources for search and discovery

00:15:57.750 --> 00:16:02.670
and will require investigations of
encrypted media, secure websites,

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:05.350
ethics, and many more aspects.

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:09.040
Do we actually understand the
stronghand that we've been dealt

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:12.910
with as Peter Kaufmann
so aptly argued

00:16:12.910 --> 00:16:16.910
in his paper assessing the
audiovisual archive market?

00:16:16.910 --> 00:16:20.390
Do we understand that our
collections have become sought

00:16:20.390 --> 00:16:23.240
after assets whether we want

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:27.220
to generate revenue or
provide it for free?

00:16:27.220 --> 00:16:30.600
The ball so to speak
is in our hands.

00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:35.070
Focal International had the
following to say, our finding show

00:16:35.070 --> 00:16:37.720
that the trade-in archives
is an important part

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:41.140
of the widened media
economy with content supplied

00:16:41.140 --> 00:16:45.700
by archives appearing in an
ever-increasing range of outlets.

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:48.100
The growing variety
consumer platforms

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:51.790
for accessing short form
long tail content means

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:56.200
that this key role will
only grow in importance.

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:01.000
Do we still experience our
archives full of stuffy old clips

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.460
of obscure events only to be found

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:08.050
in the off-chance or
wanted once-off?

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:14.450 position:56%
Our archives have inherent potential
to become dynamic businesses.

00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:18.080
While the digital content
economy has created an environment

00:17:18.080 --> 00:17:20.150
of user-generated content

00:17:20.150 --> 00:17:24.630
and the online consumers challenge
our instinct to create revenue to--

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:29.120
for ourselves with the expectation
that media content should be mostly

00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:33.600
for free, archives enjoying growing
demand from businesses as well

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:36.630
as the public or the wider public.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:41.730
It is vital for us to be proactive
in defining the future role

00:17:41.730 --> 00:17:44.980
of the archives as
curators of content.

00:17:44.980 --> 00:17:48.620
We have new channels
for content distribution

00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:51.100
for instance YouTube and Instagram.

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:54.580
We have the opportunity to
engage with new user groups.

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:57.960
