00:33:00.470 --> 00:33:04.740
But throughout the years whether
I've been preserving newsreels

00:33:04.740 --> 00:33:10.320
on 35-millimeter early stages of
my career UCLA Film and TV Archive

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:15.680
or when I moved on to try to make
research easier at the Research

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:19.360
And Study Center at the UCLA
Film and TV Archive by collecting

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:23.400
up closed caption texts
from television,

00:33:23.400 --> 00:33:29.790
news shows into a really early
database, whether I had to figure

00:33:29.790 --> 00:33:33.790 position:56%
out how-- before, there was really
much bandwidth at all with discovery

00:33:33.790 --> 00:33:38.110
to bring footage electronically
back to headquarters

00:33:38.110 --> 00:33:40.790 position:56%
from the far stretches of the world.

00:33:40.790 --> 00:33:47.630
Or now, we're really focused within
Paramount Pictures on the concept

00:33:47.630 --> 00:33:50.800
of digitally-preserving
feature films.

00:33:50.800 --> 00:33:55.030
I've always seen technology
through the lens of archiving

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:57.620
of preservation of access.

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:04.150
And I think that right now,
I feel within the world

00:34:04.150 --> 00:34:07.530
of digital archiving,
we're-- really, we're in.

00:34:07.530 --> 00:34:09.420
We're 20 to 30 years in.

00:34:09.420 --> 00:34:10.820
It's not new anymore.

00:34:10.820 --> 00:34:14.920
It's not-- We're not scratching
our heads wondering how we're going

00:34:14.920 --> 00:34:16.520
to digitize.

00:34:16.520 --> 00:34:17.820
We're there.

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:19.120
We are doing it everyday.

00:34:19.120 --> 00:34:22.410
And so, it just-- it seems
to me it's important to sort

00:34:22.410 --> 00:34:25.480
of think what does that mean
now that we are in it really.

00:34:25.480 --> 00:34:27.550
We are here 20, 30 years in.

00:34:27.550 --> 00:34:29.840
What's our role?

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:32.380
What's our responsibility?

00:34:33.670 --> 00:34:38.370
So, here are two sort of divergent
concepts of a digital archive.

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:42.090
On the top is the definition
that comes from OAIS.

00:34:42.090 --> 00:34:44.450
"Consisting of an organization
of people and systems

00:34:44.450 --> 00:34:46.700
that accepted the responsibility
to preserve information

00:34:46.700 --> 00:34:50.330
and make it available for
a designated community."

00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:53.970
A useful definition, a very useful
definition, especially I think

00:34:53.970 --> 00:34:57.710
when with the concept of
people and systems together,

00:34:57.710 --> 00:34:59.010
it's a really important one.

00:34:59.010 --> 00:35:02.460
I think that a lot of
people sometimes forget,

00:35:02.460 --> 00:35:05.270
it's as if the technology
works by itself.

00:35:05.270 --> 00:35:12.830
And the other is a recently
available online cloud-based thing

00:35:12.830 --> 00:35:17.340 position:56%
that you can put your digitally-born
materials that you've shot yourself

00:35:17.340 --> 00:35:22.240
into something that's called
a digital video archive, DVA.

00:35:22.240 --> 00:35:27.550
So, two very different ideas
of what a digital archive is.

00:35:27.550 --> 00:35:35.090
One that is-- you know, just the
beginning of different standards

00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:39.960
and ways of actually approaching a
really structured way of thinking

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:43.460
about preserving and providing
access to important materials.

00:35:43.460 --> 00:35:48.810
And the other is really kind of
a shelf that hopefully will be

00:35:48.810 --> 00:35:50.110
around for a little while.

00:35:50.110 --> 00:35:51.410
We don't know.

00:35:51.410 --> 00:35:52.710
This is a startup company.

00:35:52.710 --> 00:35:55.090
You know, it's been around I think
for maybe six months, you know,

00:35:55.090 --> 00:35:57.340
what it will be in the future.

00:35:57.340 --> 00:36:01.660 position:56%
So, it's a-- I think it's an
important thing to show that this is

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:04.140
where we are in the world where
lots of people are thinking

00:36:04.140 --> 00:36:07.610
about these definitions
in different ways.

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:12.490
This is kind of what
our archive looks

00:36:12.490 --> 00:36:15.470
like at Paramount a little bit.

00:36:15.470 --> 00:36:22.570
It's a-- This is a way that
we have to think in order

00:36:22.570 --> 00:36:27.160
to really strongly think about
the technical metadata really

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:30.290
that we need to do-- to have
to manage the feature films

00:36:30.290 --> 00:36:32.200
within our own infrastructure.

00:36:32.200 --> 00:36:35.920
And the below text is just all
sorts of words that go flying

00:36:35.920 --> 00:36:38.480
around the office pretty
much everyday.

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:45.510
But, as you can see, this kind
of very strong structuring

00:36:45.510 --> 00:36:51.740
of our basic file naming convention
is really what all this is, is--

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:57.370
has to take into what
the title of the film is,

00:36:57.370 --> 00:37:01.460
what's the current aspect ratio
of this is, whether it's--

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:05.760 position:56%
was cut for a particular
territory, and even actually was cut

00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:09.340
for a ratings reason or not.

00:37:09.340 --> 00:37:12.460
What resolution is it, where
did it come from, you know,

00:37:12.460 --> 00:37:14.720
where was it created,
which is an important part

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:16.350
of the process as well.

00:37:16.350 --> 00:37:24.540 position:56%
And I know that this kind of intense
work to systematize, to really think

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:28.790
about how our assets working
systems is incredibly important

00:37:28.790 --> 00:37:31.250
because we need to
work with technology.

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:35.080
But within the OAIS definition,
the other definitely part

00:37:35.080 --> 00:37:38.360
of this equation is the great
people that I work with everyday,

00:37:38.360 --> 00:37:43.540
the amazing people that challenge
each other constantly when we come

00:37:43.540 --> 00:37:47.820
up with a new definition
for talking about things.

00:37:47.820 --> 00:37:52.170
When-- You know, somebody who has
had a lot of system experience

00:37:52.170 --> 00:37:54.540
but not much photochemical
experience

00:37:54.540 --> 00:37:59.230
for example will really push on
someone to say, why do you need

00:37:59.230 --> 00:38:03.720
to call that black and white
interpositive fine grain, really?

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:06.030
Or is anybody going to know
what that means in the future?

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:07.920
And the arguments that
will go on there forever?

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:12.690
We work really hard to think about
not only the technical metadata

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:15.290
that we do, but the content
that we're preserving

00:38:15.290 --> 00:38:17.490
and how we're preserving that
and making that effective.

00:38:17.490 --> 00:38:22.090
So, that's an important
part of who we are.

00:38:22.090 --> 00:38:27.790
You know, as we are 20, 30 years
in, I think the default perceptions

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:30.950
of archivist still
exist outside of us

00:38:30.950 --> 00:38:33.460
and maybe inside of
us sometimes too.

00:38:33.460 --> 00:38:39.440
And it's difficult not to
sometimes when we're to be to not--

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:43.350
to be forward-thinking when
we're dealing with, you know,

00:38:43.350 --> 00:38:48.410
backlogs with subcategories
of backlogs as I have myself

00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:52.660
and deterioration issues,
legacy systems

00:38:52.660 --> 00:38:56.570
that will not probably become
anything other than legacy systems

00:38:56.570 --> 00:39:01.170
for years to come, but have to
be integrated into your latest

00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:05.540 position:56%
and greatest digital infrastructure,
budget justifications

00:39:05.540 --> 00:39:10.230
and endless PowerPoints to try
and explain what the risk is

00:39:10.230 --> 00:39:12.150
if you don't do something now.

00:39:12.150 --> 00:39:14.260
It's hard to be forward-thinking
with all

00:39:14.260 --> 00:39:15.740
that around us all the time.

00:39:15.740 --> 00:39:20.790
And it's even more hard when-- this
quote was from a recent article

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:25.630
on digital asset management which
really compares us to coal miners.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:28.850
Thank you very much.

00:39:28.850 --> 00:39:32.020
[laughter] So, you know,
it is hard to move beyond

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:34.940
that perception and
keep that in mind.

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:37.160
But, you know, I kind of
think that's OK anyway

00:39:37.160 --> 00:39:41.010
because that is part of who we are.

00:39:41.010 --> 00:39:45.270
So, you know, mass digitization,
a huge impact obviously

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:48.740 position:56%
on anybody that's calling themselves
a librarian or an archivist.

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:51.630
A hundred million books, over a 100
million books have been digitized.

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:55.100
I think-- And maybe that somebody--

00:39:55.100 --> 00:39:59.130
oh no, there's no more book
people in the room anymore.

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:00.800
But I believe and I just--

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:02.850
Please correct me if anybody
knows this is right or wrong.

00:40:02.850 --> 00:40:08.020
I think every book before
1800 is now been digitized,

00:40:08.020 --> 00:40:10.630
something like that.

00:40:10.630 --> 00:40:13.460
And these are publicly-searched--
is that right?

00:40:13.460 --> 00:40:14.760
Is that wrong?

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:16.060
Somebody say something?

00:40:16.060 --> 00:40:18.330
By the way, anytime anybody wants
to interrupt me and correct me

00:40:18.330 --> 00:40:20.460
or ask me questions, you're
more than welcome to--

00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:22.520
I don't have to just keep talking.

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:26.560
But-- And the whole idea is

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:28.940
to make these things
publicly-searchable online.

00:40:28.940 --> 00:40:30.620
That is the idea of
the digitization.

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:33.340
And that is fantastic.

00:40:33.340 --> 00:40:34.640
It is amazing.

00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:37.130
It has made things-- It has
made people be able to do

00:40:37.130 --> 00:40:41.310
so much more kinds of research
all over the world and be able

00:40:41.310 --> 00:40:45.490
to really, you know, sort
of do things from distances

00:40:45.490 --> 00:40:47.750
that they were never
able to do before.

00:40:47.750 --> 00:40:50.580
I mean, that kind of
access is incredible.

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:58.430
And within moving images, you know,
within a very short time, you know,

00:40:58.430 --> 00:41:04.550
I went from saying things like, you
know, one day, we'll be able to go

00:41:04.550 --> 00:41:09.830
on the internet and we'll be able
to actually like click on something

00:41:09.830 --> 00:41:14.400
and watch and listen at the
same time to actually being able

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:17.410
to manage that and having
that be a major part

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:21.440
of what Paramount Pictures does
everyday is to move our content

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:25.660
on to be streamed all
over the world.

00:41:25.660 --> 00:41:29.520
This quote here, "Update,
cat bombs more prevalent

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:34.710
than previously thought" which
I just loved, is from an article

00:41:34.710 --> 00:41:41.980
from the Atlantic, a guy who
writes a lot about technology

00:41:41.980 --> 00:41:50.760
who had picked up on a researcher's
paper on the fact that there was

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:57.620
in fact in this 16th century
manuscript what looked like a cat

00:41:57.620 --> 00:42:01.740
with a bomb on its back,
and actually had found more

00:42:01.740 --> 00:42:05.420
than one cat with a
bomb on its back.

00:42:05.420 --> 00:42:08.690
And to me, it just
sort of articulates it.

00:42:08.690 --> 00:42:10.360 position:56%
Yeah, we have all this stuff online.

00:42:10.360 --> 00:42:12.230
We have researchers
looking into this stuff.

00:42:12.230 --> 00:42:16.120
But we also have, you know,
the clickbait universe as well

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:18.550
who is going to pick up on this

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:22.320
and maybe trivialize what was a
really important piece of research

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:25.780
or maybe talk about this in
ways that had nothing to do

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:31.760
with what the original, you know,
fundraising proposal said about,

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:34.900 position:56%
you know, scanning these manuscripts
and how critical they were.

00:42:34.900 --> 00:42:36.200
But that exists.

00:42:36.200 --> 00:42:37.650
And that's part of our world now.

00:42:37.650 --> 00:42:39.350
We can't go back from it.

00:42:39.350 --> 00:42:42.080
Maybe we will mature
beyond clickbait land.

00:42:42.080 --> 00:42:43.380
That would be lovely.

00:42:43.380 --> 00:42:44.880
I would love to think
about a world, what we did.

00:42:44.880 --> 00:42:47.540
Maybe this is just a transition
we're going through right now.

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:50.110
But it's here, and it's
part of what happens

00:42:50.110 --> 00:42:52.810
when we make things
accessible on out there.

00:42:52.810 --> 00:42:56.980
You know, and the other
thing I think that happens

00:42:56.980 --> 00:42:59.630
when we digitize things
whether it's books

00:42:59.630 --> 00:43:01.340
or whether it's moving images is

00:43:01.340 --> 00:43:05.130
that they're not what
they used to be anymore.

00:43:05.130 --> 00:43:09.200
I mean, even though the content
is there, the way that we work

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:15.340
with them is-- you know,
is-- does obviously change.

00:43:15.340 --> 00:43:19.610
We-- If we are providing
access to moving images online,

00:43:19.610 --> 00:43:24.410
we don't necessarily have to have
several different flatbed editors

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:26.360
for which we can playback
16-millimeter

00:43:26.360 --> 00:43:30.440
and 35-millimeter prints if those
things are available online.

00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:32.840
So, that skill and that
understanding of how

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:34.870
that works is going to change.

00:43:34.870 --> 00:43:36.670
I mean obviously, as we look--

00:43:36.670 --> 00:43:39.350
if you look at any kind of
job descriptions that are

00:43:39.350 --> 00:43:44.380
out there today, coding, knowing
some kind of Python scripting

00:43:44.380 --> 00:43:46.820
or other kind of scripting
is a regular part

00:43:46.820 --> 00:43:49.240
of a digital archivist
job description now.

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:50.670
That wasn't around anymore.

00:43:50.670 --> 00:43:52.580
Our jobs are changing.

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:54.650
That's part of what we're doing.

00:43:54.650 --> 00:43:58.200
And so, just trying
to think of that,

00:43:58.200 --> 00:44:02.870
the content without the
technology that surrounds it is--

00:44:02.870 --> 00:44:04.170
we can't just do it anymore.

00:44:04.170 --> 00:44:05.950
It's just-- It's here.

00:44:05.950 --> 00:44:13.120
But within that, I think, you know,
what's also happening is, you know,

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:16.070
we do have some really
incredibly deep

00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:18.680
and useful skills as archivists.

00:44:18.680 --> 00:44:21.810
And we need not-- we need
to remember that always.

00:44:21.810 --> 00:44:29.240
You know, I think this little quote
here is another recent article on,

00:44:29.240 --> 00:44:33.140 position:56%
you know, data mining, big data,
data science, call it what you will.

00:44:33.140 --> 00:44:37.450
And this concept of "dark
data" which I just love

00:44:37.450 --> 00:44:42.660
which is roughly translated
I think, unstructured data.

00:44:42.660 --> 00:44:46.180
And what they're really saying--

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:48.610
what they were saying in
this article is that, hey,

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:51.180 position:56%
this metadata thing might be useful.

00:44:51.180 --> 00:44:54.410
That there might be
something to that,

00:44:54.410 --> 00:44:57.010
actually having some
structured data in there.

00:44:57.010 --> 00:44:58.880 position:56%
And they're actually talking about--

00:44:58.880 --> 00:45:01.920
So many people actually
put things into dark data.

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:04.690
And most of the time, I think
they're talking about just,

00:45:04.690 --> 00:45:10.060
you know, maybe geospatial
data or, you know, call--

00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:12.270
phone metadata, things like that.

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:13.570
But they're also saying,
oh, wow, you know,

00:45:13.570 --> 00:45:18.260
people actually have e-mails and
files that they put into systems,

00:45:18.260 --> 00:45:21.150
so a little scary, but
