00:47:50.090 --> 00:47:56.550
Another quote from a recent article

00:47:56.550 --> 00:47:59.480
about digital asset management
system, and this is something

00:47:59.480 --> 00:48:02.520
that is near and dear to
my heart too which is,

00:48:02.520 --> 00:48:06.130
this content I call
asset transparency

00:48:06.130 --> 00:48:07.430
which is a horrible phrase.

00:48:07.430 --> 00:48:08.730
I need to come up with another one.

00:48:08.730 --> 00:48:11.210
But the idea is that when we were--

00:48:11.210 --> 00:48:14.050
at Paramount, when we were building
our digital preservation system,

00:48:14.050 --> 00:48:16.820
a key philosophical foundation--

00:48:16.820 --> 00:48:21.230
foundational philosophy was
that we needed to build a system

00:48:21.230 --> 00:48:24.120
that we could take
all of the assets.

00:48:24.120 --> 00:48:28.540 position:56%
And by that, I mean, each individual
file that makes up the picture

00:48:28.540 --> 00:48:33.360
of a feature film, and each
individual WAV file that makes

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:38.790
up the track that goes along with
that feature film, the video files

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:42.120
that represent the trailer,
the JPEGs that represent all

00:48:42.120 --> 00:48:45.200
of the photographic
stills, all those assets

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:49.310
and all their metadata need
to be able to move them

00:48:49.310 --> 00:48:52.660
out of the current digital
asset management system

00:48:52.660 --> 00:48:56.300
and the infrastructure we have
now and into something else.

00:48:56.300 --> 00:48:58.890
Because I know the
software will go away.

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:01.150
I know the hardware will change.

00:49:01.150 --> 00:49:03.930
That-- Those are the
things I know the most.

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:07.820
What-- And what-- But what I need
to do is maintain the longevity

00:49:07.820 --> 00:49:10.130
and the permanence of the assets.

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:14.510
And so in order to do that,
I think it's really important

00:49:14.510 --> 00:49:20.910
to know the machine for-- which
is know what your system is made

00:49:20.910 --> 00:49:22.810
out of, what are its
bits and pieces.

00:49:22.810 --> 00:49:25.880
I think that is something
that we need to know better.

00:49:25.880 --> 00:49:34.890 position:56%
I mean, within my career, I've seen,
you know, the change from, you know,

00:49:34.890 --> 00:49:42.250
when you had-- everyone had
their own data storage system,

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:45.840
their own tape library or their set
of servers they had in the basement

00:49:45.840 --> 00:49:50.500
or they had some place on their
facility to now moving to a lot

00:49:50.500 --> 00:49:53.820
of people using cloud-based
infrastructures

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:55.120
and what does that mean?

00:49:55.120 --> 00:49:58.170
It means different
technology roles change.

00:49:58.170 --> 00:50:03.620
This concept of DevOps,
the development operations,

00:50:03.620 --> 00:50:08.880
is a new sort of catch-all job
description for many people

00:50:08.880 --> 00:50:10.670
that work in different
technology fields.

00:50:10.670 --> 00:50:14.770
And what it means is, they have to
do hardware and software together

00:50:14.770 --> 00:50:18.190
where it used to be very,
very segregated across,

00:50:18.190 --> 00:50:21.230
you had system administrators,
you had software developers,

00:50:21.230 --> 00:50:23.470
you had analyst, very segregated.

00:50:23.470 --> 00:50:25.280
Now, everything is
getting smooshed together.

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:28.100
It's important to know
that because that--

00:50:28.100 --> 00:50:31.500
you're going to need to interact
with those people as you go.

00:50:31.500 --> 00:50:38.400
So knowing what you have now and
also specifically like for example

00:50:38.400 --> 00:50:42.090
at Paramount, not only do I have
my digital asset management system,

00:50:42.090 --> 00:50:47.900
I am absolutely dependent on
other databases within the studio

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:52.530
to provide me with key metadata
about my assets, whether it's--

00:50:52.530 --> 00:50:56.440
there is a title database for
example that I must interact with.

00:50:56.440 --> 00:50:59.320
There is a rights database
that I must interact with.

00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:03.840
So knowing about those
systems and their fragility

00:51:03.840 --> 00:51:06.560
because often there is
that, their legacy systems,

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:10.240
it may not be replaced for a while
what information I need is also a

00:51:10.240 --> 00:51:11.540
part of my job.

00:51:11.540 --> 00:51:14.230
So I think that's another
but I think again--

00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:19.360
I think we have the skills for that
because I think naturally we do see

00:51:19.360 --> 00:51:24.740
because we've been working
so hard on really collecting

00:51:24.740 --> 00:51:26.600
and documenting collections.

00:51:26.600 --> 00:51:30.200
We can see in our heads what things
we need from different places.

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:35.780
So I think we have
the skills to do that.

00:51:35.780 --> 00:51:40.940
So distract-tech, this is my phrase
I won't patent it or anything

00:51:40.940 --> 00:51:45.870
but the-- there's thing called
AdTech and MarTech I don't know

00:51:45.870 --> 00:51:48.270
if you've come across
this concept or--

00:51:48.270 --> 00:51:54.340 position:56%
but right, really what that means is
that advertisers and marketers are

00:51:54.340 --> 00:51:56.260
of course becoming
really savvy about how

00:51:56.260 --> 00:52:00.640
to make sure you're
getting as many things,

00:52:00.640 --> 00:52:04.420
so it was possible whenever
you interact with the interwebs

00:52:04.420 --> 00:52:07.020
or anything connected to it.

00:52:07.020 --> 00:52:12.950
And they, you know, are in the data
science realm, they are in trying

00:52:12.950 --> 00:52:16.310
to make sure that whatever you're,
you know, buying is connected

00:52:16.310 --> 00:52:19.230
to something you bought
before all these kind of stuff

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:24.760 position:56%
and this quote is I think really apt
which is somebody sort of starting

00:52:24.760 --> 00:52:28.590
to complain if there's really not a
lot of substance there and it does.

00:52:28.590 --> 00:52:29.890
I think, you know, in some cases,

00:52:29.890 --> 00:52:32.530
there is some really good probably
programming behind it but a lot

00:52:32.530 --> 00:52:36.890 position:56%
of it is marketing to themselves,
you know, where our company is going

00:52:36.890 --> 00:52:40.350
to save all your, you know,
to solve all your advertising

00:52:40.350 --> 00:52:42.140
in marketing problems.

00:52:42.140 --> 00:52:46.880
And I just put his sort of hashtag
"we've always had substance,"

00:52:46.880 --> 00:52:50.260
which is-- this is again
what we have as archivists,

00:52:50.260 --> 00:52:53.600 position:56%
is we have the collections, we have
the contents, we have the substance,

00:52:53.600 --> 00:52:59.130
you know, that it's easy I think
to get caught up in the fact

00:52:59.130 --> 00:53:04.510
that if we have digitized a lot
of materials, we feel, you know,

00:53:04.510 --> 00:53:08.300
we must get, you know, push
something out via Twitter

00:53:08.300 --> 00:53:11.920
or Facebook, or Instagram
or Snapchat or something

00:53:11.920 --> 00:53:14.140
into the universe everyday.

00:53:14.140 --> 00:53:16.590
It's an important part of
getting the word out there

00:53:16.590 --> 00:53:18.610
about our digital collections.

00:53:18.610 --> 00:53:21.560
And maybe that's a great idea,
maybe that isn't, I don't know.

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:26.070
But I think it is, it can
be, you know, sort of,

00:53:26.070 --> 00:53:31.150 position:56%
it could potentially be distracting
too from our mission from my opinion

00:53:31.150 --> 00:53:34.780
that just getting the word
out about our collections

00:53:34.780 --> 00:53:37.240
and spending an enormous amount
of time doing without thinking

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:43.270
about why it could carry
some risks just a thought.

00:53:43.270 --> 00:53:49.250
You know, this phrase iTunes
metadata decimation is actually a

00:53:49.250 --> 00:53:52.250
quote from a friend of mine
who was talking about how--

00:53:52.250 --> 00:53:57.840
they've had iTunes for, you know,
oh gosh, a decade or so or more

00:53:57.840 --> 00:54:03.910
and have purchased a lot of
music and then, you know,

00:54:03.910 --> 00:54:08.030
and kept very good, you know, he
is very good personal archivist,

00:54:08.030 --> 00:54:11.890
very good care of his
iTunes library overtime.

00:54:11.890 --> 00:54:21.050 position:56%
And then decided to go to the iCloud
and push his library up there and lo

00:54:21.050 --> 00:54:26.990
and behold, new versions of
music actually replaced the ones

00:54:26.990 --> 00:54:28.960
that he had originally purchased.

00:54:28.960 --> 00:54:33.940
You know and iTunes mainly stop
the music, what's your problem.

00:54:33.940 --> 00:54:38.360 position:56%
But, you know, this is I think a key
and an interesting concept to keep

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:46.230
in mind as archivists, right, which
is that I can see a world where,

00:54:46.230 --> 00:54:50.200
let's say, you know, Paramount
Pictures, oh I don't know,

00:54:50.200 --> 00:54:54.500
is bought up by, oh, I don't know,
a Chinese studio that could happen.

00:54:54.500 --> 00:54:58.630
And the Chinese studios
actually digitized the bunch

00:54:58.630 --> 00:55:02.960
of Paramount Pictures on their
own for some reason overtime

00:55:02.960 --> 00:55:05.900
and they just want to merge
our libraries why not, right?

00:55:05.900 --> 00:55:07.380
It's no big deal.

00:55:07.380 --> 00:55:12.780
Well, we're-- but I've spent, you
know, most of my time making sure

00:55:12.780 --> 00:55:17.040
that when I have Saturday
Night Fever,

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:19.190
I know it's Saturday night fever.

00:55:19.190 --> 00:55:24.130 position:56%
I know that I have captured the best
possible resolution of that image

00:55:24.130 --> 00:55:27.790 position:56%
that I know that that both technical
and descriptive metadata is

00:55:27.790 --> 00:55:31.580
as accurate as possible that
I've spent this time doing it

00:55:31.580 --> 00:55:33.580
and I don't want to lose that.

00:55:33.580 --> 00:55:39.060
And that's an important key thing
and it's a concept to provenance.

00:55:39.060 --> 00:55:44.070
And I think it is going to be much
more important for us to find ways

00:55:44.070 --> 00:55:47.280
of authenticating and
verifying and making sure

00:55:47.280 --> 00:55:52.920
that we have actual information
about different versions of assets

00:55:52.920 --> 00:55:55.450
and materials as we go forward.

00:55:55.450 --> 00:55:58.380
I was talking to Bert a
little bit before about--

00:55:58.380 --> 00:56:01.480
just about law enforcement
and not the obvious need

00:56:01.480 --> 00:56:04.230
for evidentiary provenance.

00:56:04.230 --> 00:56:09.050 position:56%
So this is, you know, to me this-- I
have a tough girl up there because,

00:56:09.050 --> 00:56:12.390 position:56%
you know, nobody is going to take my
Saturday Night Fever away from me.

00:56:12.390 --> 00:56:16.350
You know, that is my
job to make sure

00:56:16.350 --> 00:56:19.450
that Saturday Night Fever
exists in the best possible way.

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:23.690
Or more, perhaps, you
know, a film like Nebraska

00:56:23.690 --> 00:56:29.100 position:56%
which was digitally shot and doesn't
have a chance for me to go back

00:56:29.100 --> 00:56:32.620
to some sort of analog
provenance if I need to.

00:56:32.620 --> 00:56:35.220
So this to me, you
know, this is our--

00:56:35.220 --> 00:56:39.420
one of our responsibilities as far
as I see it in the digital realm is

00:56:39.420 --> 00:56:44.350
to make sure that we are the
keepers of the real stuff.

00:56:44.350 --> 00:56:47.120
We're really good at that and
we shouldn't lose that just

00:56:47.120 --> 00:56:52.320
because it's digital or, and so you
were talking about crowd sourcing

00:56:52.320 --> 00:56:55.660
and other kinds of, you know,
that kind of interaction with that

00:56:55.660 --> 00:57:00.830
and I think that none of that is
wrong or off but it's still our job

00:57:00.830 --> 00:57:03.510
in the end to keep that
provenance in that authority

00:57:03.510 --> 00:57:06.440 position:56%
and that verification in my opinion.

